outputs.output:
{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "When dark clouds roll in, you check your weather app showing \"70% chance of rain.\" That percentage helps you decide: bring an umbrella or risk it? You're using probability to make a practical choice about your day.",
      "title": "Your Morning Weather Check"
    },
    {
      "text": "Swiping right on a dating app, you weigh whether someone's profile suggests compatibility. You're unconsciously estimating: \"What's the probability this person and I would click?\" — using limited info to assess romantic potential.",
      "title": "Dating App Decisions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your favorite team is down by 3 with 2 minutes left. Commentators say \"They have a 15% chance to win.\" You're watching probability unfold in real-time, deciding whether to stay glued to the screen or start your evening.",
      "title": "The Final Minutes of the Game"
    },
    {
      "text": "At the pharmacy, you read that a medication works for 85% of patients. You're using probability to decide: Is this worth trying? The percentage helps you have realistic expectations about your treatment.",
      "title": "Choosing Medical Treatment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Before a road trip, you notice your tire tread is worn. You think: \"It'll probably be fine\" or \"There's too much risk of a blowout.\" You're estimating failure probability to decide whether to replace them now.",
      "title": "The Worn Tire Dilemma"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your phone shows \"5% battery remaining.\" Will it last until you get home, or should you find a charger now? You're quickly calculating the probability of making it based on distance and usage patterns.",
      "title": "The Dying Phone Battery"
    },
    {
      "text": "A recruiter says \"We're interviewing 50 candidates for 2 positions.\" Instantly, you grasp your odds are about 4%. This probability assessment helps you decide how much to invest emotionally in this opportunity.",
      "title": "Job Interview Odds"
    },
    {
      "text": "On a game show, you're offered $5,000 guaranteed or a 40% chance at $15,000. Contestants use probability thinking to weigh certain smaller rewards against risky larger ones — a decision you face in various life choices.",
      "title": "The Game Show Gamble"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your flight is delayed, and you might miss your connection. The gate agent can't promise anything, but you assess: \"If we leave in 10 minutes, I probably make it.\" You're estimating probabilities to plan your next move.",
      "title": "The Tight Connection"
    },
    {
      "text": "Reading food labels, you see \"May contain traces of nuts.\" You have a mild allergy. The word \"may\" signals low but non-zero probability, helping you decide if the risk is acceptable for that snack.",
      "title": "The Allergy Warning"
    },
    {
      "text": "In poker, you hold two pairs and calculate: \"What's the probability my opponent has something better?\" Skilled players constantly update probability estimates based on cards shown and betting patterns.",
      "title": "The Poker Hand"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your backup drive is 3 years old. Tech forums say drives typically last 5-7 years. You're thinking probabilistically: \"How likely is failure this year?\" to decide whether to buy a replacement before disaster strikes.",
      "title": "The Aging Hard Drive"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "After a hurricane, bottled water at your local store jumps from $4 to $12 a pack. Demand surged because everyone needs clean water, but supply couldn't keep up. Suppliers rush more water to the area, and within days, prices start dropping back down.",
      "title": "Storm Water Shortages"
    },
    {
      "text": "Concert tickets drop to $20 the day before the show because the venue still has hundreds of empty seats. The band would rather fill the arena at a discount than play to a half-empty room. Low demand at the original price forced the price adjustment.",
      "title": "Last-Minute Concert Deals"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your favorite taco truck raises prices by $2 when they park outside a sold-out stadium. They know thousands of hungry fans have limited food options nearby. High demand with restricted supply lets them charge more, and people still line up.",
      "title": "Food Trucks at Big Events"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gas stations on opposite corners constantly adjust their prices throughout the day, undercutting each other by a penny or two. They're competing for your business in real-time, and prices settle where enough drivers choose each station to keep both profitable.",
      "title": "Corner Gas Station Wars"
    },
    {
      "text": "When the new iPhone launches, scalpers buy dozens and resell them for double the price online. Apple's limited initial supply can't meet massive demand, creating a gap that resellers exploit. As Apple ships more units, those inflated resale prices crash.",
      "title": "iPhone Launch Day Frenzy"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your local coffee shop experiments with different morning prices and notices $4 sells out their pastries by 9am, but $5 leaves some unsold. They settle on $4.50, where they sell almost everything without running out too early. That's their sweet spot.",
      "title": "Coffee Shop Price Testing"
    },
    {
      "text": "Streaming services lose subscribers when they raise prices from $10 to $15. Some customers decide the service isn't worth the extra cost and cancel. The company has to balance higher revenue per subscriber against losing customers to competitors.",
      "title": "Streaming Price Hikes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Farmers' market vendors drop tomato prices in August when everyone's garden is producing. Supply floods the market while demand stays steady, so sellers compete by lowering prices to move their inventory before it spoils.",
      "title": "Peak Harvest Season Glut"
    },
    {
      "text": "Uber charges you 2.5x surge pricing on New Year's Eve because thousands of riders need cars while drivers stay home with family. The high price encourages more drivers to work and discourages some riders from taking trips, balancing the system.",
      "title": "Ride-Share Surge Pricing"
    },
    {
      "text": "Black Friday doorbuster deals pack stores at 5am with TVs marked down 60%. Retailers intentionally create excess demand with ultra-low prices to drive foot traffic, knowing they'll only lose money on a few units while selling tons of regular-priced items.",
      "title": "Doorbuster Loss Leaders"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your city's housing market sees rents jump 25% in a year because new tech companies moved in, bringing thousands of employees. Demand for apartments exploded while new construction takes years, creating a gap where landlords can charge much more.",
      "title": "Tech Town Rent Spikes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sneaker brands release limited-edition collaborations that sell out in minutes at $200, then resell for $1,000. By restricting supply while building hype, they've created artificial scarcity that superfans will pay premiums for.",
      "title": "Limited Sneaker Drops"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "When you search for a file on your computer, the system checks the current folder, then recursively searches every subfolder inside. Each subfolder search works the same way — check here, then check subfolders. That's how it explores your entire directory tree.",
      "title": "Finding Files on Your Computer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Google's search algorithm ranks pages partly by looking at what links to them, which depends on what links to THOSE pages, and so on. Each page's importance is defined by the importance of pages linking to it — pure recursion.",
      "title": "How Google Ranks Web Pages"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you're watching Inception and the characters go into a dream within a dream within a dream, each layer follows the same rules. The movie uses recursion as its entire structure — the same scenario repeating at different depths.",
      "title": "Dreams Within Dreams in Inception"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fractals like the Mandelbrot set zoom infinitely. Each zoom reveals the same pattern repeated at a smaller scale. Artists and mathematicians use this recursive property to create infinitely complex images from simple rules.",
      "title": "Fractals and Infinite Zoom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your family tree is recursive — you have parents, who have parents, who have parents. Each person's ancestry follows the identical pattern of two parents branching backward through time.",
      "title": "Your Family Tree Structure"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you're trying to sort a deck of cards, you might split it in half, sort each half, then merge them. Sorting each half? Split again, sort, merge. That's merge sort — the classic recursive algorithm behind many sorting features.",
      "title": "Sorting Your Streaming Queue"
    },
    {
      "text": "A mirror facing another mirror creates infinite reflections. Each reflection contains a reflection of the reflection. You're seeing recursion in physical space — the same image repeated within itself endlessly.",
      "title": "The Infinite Mirror Effect"
    },
    {
      "text": "Compound interest calculates today's balance from yesterday's balance plus interest. Yesterday's balance came from the day before in the same way. Your investment grows through a recursive calculation repeated daily.",
      "title": "Your Savings Account Growing"
    },
    {
      "text": "When Tower of Hanoi puzzle solvers move disks, they use recursion: move n-1 disks to spare peg, move largest disk to target, move those n-1 disks to target. The n-1 problem solves exactly like the original, just smaller.",
      "title": "Puzzle Games Like Tower of Hanoi"
    },
    {
      "text": "JSON and XML data nest objects inside objects inside objects. When a program parses this, it processes each level the same way: read the container, recursively process what's inside, no matter how deep it goes.",
      "title": "Nested Data in Apps and Websites"
    },
    {
      "text": "That Russian nesting doll set on your shelf — matryoshka dolls — is physical recursion. Each doll contains a smaller version of itself, following the same pattern until you reach the smallest one that can't open.",
      "title": "Russian Nesting Dolls"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you're debugging code and trace a function call that calls another function that calls another, you're following a recursive chain. Your debugger's call stack shows each level waiting for the deeper one to finish.",
      "title": "Debugging Function Call Chains"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Você escolhe um shampoo porque viu um influenciador usando. Ele tem cabelo lindo — certamente o produto funciona, certo? Isso é o viés da autoridade: confiamos em celebridades mesmo quando não são especialistas no assunto.",
      "title": "A Prateleira do Supermercado"
    },
    {
      "text": "Seu time perdeu? 'O juiz roubou!' Ele ganhou? 'Merecemos!' Esse é o viés de autobenefício: atribuímos sucessos ao nosso talento e fracassos a fatores externos. Assim protegemos nossa autoestima, mas evitamos aprender com erros.",
      "title": "Torcendo no Estádio"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você segue apenas pessoas com opiniões políticas parecidas nas redes sociais. Seu feed confirma diariamente o que você pensa. Essa bolha reforça suas crenças e faz o 'outro lado' parecer cada vez mais extremo.",
      "title": "Sua Bolha nas Redes Sociais"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aquele ex que você idealizou por meses? Você lembra só dos momentos bons e esquece as brigas constantes. O viés da memória cor-de-rosa edita o passado, fazendo relações problemáticas parecerem perfeitas.",
      "title": "Pensando no Ex"
    },
    {
      "text": "'Todo mundo está comprando, deve ser bom!' Você entra no restaurante lotado em vez do vazio ao lado. O viés de manada nos faz copiar as escolhas da maioria, assumindo que multidões não podem estar erradas.",
      "title": "Fila no Restaurante"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você acha que dirige melhor que a média dos motoristas. Estatisticamente impossível que todos estejam acima da média, mas 80% das pessoas acreditam nisso. É o viés de superconfiança trabalhando.",
      "title": "Ao Volante"
    },
    {
      "text": "Vê notícia de assalto e decide que a cidade está mais perigosa. Na verdade, a criminalidade caiu, mas a notícia recente está fresca na memória. O viés da disponibilidade nos faz julgar pela informação mais acessível.",
      "title": "Assistindo ao Jornal"
    },
    {
      "text": "'Investir em Bitcoin? Nunca deu certo pra mim.' Você ignora que perdeu dinheiro porque entrou no pico e vendeu no pânico — culpa o ativo, não suas decisões. O viés de atribuição externa nos protege do desconforto.",
      "title": "Conversando sobre Investimentos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você gasta R$ 150 no cinema (ingresso, pipoca, estacionamento) mesmo o filme sendo horrível. 'Já paguei, vou ficar até o fim!' O viés do custo afundado nos prende a decisões ruins porque já investimos nelas.",
      "title": "No Cinema Chato"
    },
    {
      "text": "Conhece alguém novo e decide em 5 segundos se é confiável. Baseado em quê? Roupas, jeito de falar, um sorriso. O efeito halo nos faz julgar características que não vemos pela primeira impressão que tivemos.",
      "title": "Primeira Impressão na Entrevista"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Cuando tu médico te pide terminar el antibiótico completo, está luchando contra la selección natural. Las bacterias más resistentes sobreviven dosis incompletas y se multiplican, creando cepas cada vez más difíciles de eliminar.",
      "title": "Bacterias Resistentes a Antibióticos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los mosquitos que pican de día en lugar de noche están ganando terreno en ciudades donde rociamos insecticidas al anochecer. Su horario 'raro' les permite sobrevivir y reproducirse mientras sus primos nocturnos mueren.",
      "title": "Mosquitos que Cambian su Horario"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las polillas en Londres solían ser claras, perfectas para camuflarse en árboles cubiertos de líquenes. Cuando la revolución industrial oscureció los troncos con hollín, las polillas oscuras se volvieron comunes en solo décadas.",
      "title": "Polillas de Manchester"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tu perro labrador que adora el agua desciende de perros que pescaban mejor que otros. Los criadores eligieron a los mejores nadadores durante generaciones, acelerando lo que la naturaleza hace más lentamente.",
      "title": "Razas de Perros Especializadas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las cucarachas están evolucionando aversión a las trampas de azúcar que usamos contra ellas. Las que evitan lo dulce sobreviven, reproducen, y ahora tenemos cucarachas que ignoran nuestros cebos tradicionales.",
      "title": "Cucarachas Anti-Azúcar"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los peces en ríos contaminados con químicos industriales están desarrollando tolerancia en pocas generaciones. Los que sobreviven el agua tóxica tienen descendientes con la misma resistencia, salvando poblaciones enteras.",
      "title": "Peces en Aguas Contaminadas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las plantas urbanas florecen más temprano cada década. Las que brotan pronto en el clima urbano más cálido producen más semillas, transmitiendo esos genes de 'madrugadora' a sus crías.",
      "title": "Flores de Ciudad"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los elefantes africanos nacen cada vez más sin colmillos. La caza furtiva eliminó a los de colmillos grandes durante décadas, dejando reproducirse principalmente a hembras sin colmillos o con colmillos pequeños.",
      "title": "Elefantes sin Colmillos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las ratas de Nueva York pueden metabolizar comida chatarra mejor que sus primas rurales. Generaciones sobreviviendo de pizza y hot dogs favorecieron genes que procesan grasas y azúcares de forma más eficiente.",
      "title": "Ratas Urbanas Adaptadas"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Every time you unlock your phone with your face, machine learning compares your current appearance to thousands of stored images. Different lighting, angles, even new glasses — it recognizes you because it learned from countless examples.",
      "title": "Your Phone's Face Recognition"
    },
    {
      "text": "That playlist Spotify creates 'just for you' isn't random. Machine learning analyzes millions of listening patterns — what you skip, replay, or save — and predicts songs you'll probably like based on similar listeners.",
      "title": "Music App Recommendations"
    },
    {
      "text": "When Netflix suggests 'Because you watched...', machine learning has studied viewing patterns from millions of subscribers. It noticed people who loved show A also binged show B, predicting you might too.",
      "title": "Netflix's 'You Might Like' Queue"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gmail's spam filter learned from billions of emails what spam looks like. It spots patterns — suspicious phrases, sketchy links, weird formatting — that humans flagged as junk, keeping your inbox clean automatically.",
      "title": "Email Spam Protection"
    },
    {
      "text": "Those product recommendations on Amazon? Machine learning tracks what items are frequently bought together and predicts what you might need. Bought a camera? Here are memory cards and cases other photographers purchased.",
      "title": "Shopping Site Suggestions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your bank's fraud alert system learned from millions of transactions what 'normal' looks like for you. Suddenly buying electronics in another country at 3am? The pattern breaks, triggering an alert to protect you.",
      "title": "Credit Card Fraud Detection"
    },
    {
      "text": "Instagram's Explore page learns what content makes you pause, like, or share. Over time, it predicts which posts will grab your attention based on patterns from your past behavior and similar users.",
      "title": "Social Media Content Feeds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Voice assistants like Siri or Alexa learned to understand speech by training on millions of voice recordings. Different accents, background noise, mumbling — they improve by learning from diverse examples of human speech.",
      "title": "Voice-Activated Assistants"
    },
    {
      "text": "Google Photos automatically organizes pictures by recognizing faces, pets, and locations. It learned from billions of images what beaches, birthdays, and your dog look like, tagging photos without you lifting a finger.",
      "title": "Automatic Photo Organization"
    },
    {
      "text": "Autocorrect on your keyboard learned from massive text datasets how words typically flow together. It predicts what you meant to type based on patterns of common mistakes and word combinations.",
      "title": "Smartphone Autocorrect"
    },
    {
      "text": "Maps apps predict traffic delays by learning from millions of phones traveling the same routes. Slow on Highway 101 at 8am on Tuesdays? Machine learning spotted that pattern and adjusts your estimated arrival time.",
      "title": "Navigation and Traffic Predictions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Smart thermostats like Nest learn your temperature preferences throughout the day. Home by 6pm, sleep by 11pm — it detects patterns in your routine and adjusts heating automatically without you programming it.",
      "title": "Smart Home Temperature Control"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Your savings account shows $1,043 after a year on a $1,000 deposit. That extra $43 isn't just $40 in interest—it's $40 plus interest earned on previous interest payments. Your money literally made money.",
      "title": "Your Bank Statement"
    },
    {
      "text": "That $5,000 credit card balance at 18% APR? If you only pay minimums, you're being hit with compound interest working against you. Interest gets added to your balance, then next month's interest includes that added amount.",
      "title": "Credit Card Trap"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your 401(k) contributions seem small now, but that $200 monthly deposit at 25 becomes $500,000 by 65. The first deposits have 40 years to compound—they do most of the heavy lifting while you sleep.",
      "title": "Retirement Account Magic"
    },
    {
      "text": "Student loans accrue interest during college. Graduate with $30,000 in loans, and by the time repayment starts, it's $33,000. That extra $3,000? Interest that's now part of your principal, earning its own interest.",
      "title": "Student Loan Surprise"
    },
    {
      "text": "Reinvest those Netflix dividends instead of cashing out? In 10 years, those small quarterly payments compound into meaningful wealth. Each dividend buys more shares, which generate more dividends.",
      "title": "Dividend Reinvestment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your YouTube channel gains 100 subscribers, who share videos bringing 110 more, who bring 121 more. That's compound growth—each wave of viewers creates the next wave, exponentially expanding your reach.",
      "title": "Social Media Growth"
    },
    {
      "text": "Leave $10,000 in a checking account earning nothing, or invest it at 7%? In 30 years, that choice means having $10,000 versus $76,000. Compounding doesn't just build wealth—it punishes waiting.",
      "title": "The Cost of Cash"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your home appreciates 3% annually. Sounds modest, but that $300,000 house becomes $728,000 in 30 years. Each year's gain becomes part of next year's base, multiplying your equity while you live there.",
      "title": "Real Estate Appreciation"
    },
    {
      "text": "Payday loans compound weekly or even daily. Borrow $500 and owe $575 in two weeks. Roll it over? That new interest compounds on top of old interest, trapping borrowers in devastating cycles.",
      "title": "Predatory Lending"
    },
    {
      "text": "Start investing at 25 versus 35? That 10-year head start means the first person contributes less total money but ends with twice the retirement fund. Early contributions get decades more compounding time.",
      "title": "The Early Bird Wins"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Toda vez que você respira, está usando oxigênio que uma planta liberou. Árvores no parque, grama no quintal, algas no oceano — todas bombeando O2 para o ar enquanto você lê isso.",
      "title": "O Ar Que Você Respira"
    },
    {
      "text": "Seu café da manhã — pão, frutas, cereal — começou com fotossíntese. Mesmo a carne vem de animais que comeram plantas. Toda cadeia alimentar do planeta começa com luz solar capturada por folhas.",
      "title": "Café da Manhã Solar"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aquela sombra gostosa da árvore em dia quente? Ela está puxando CO2 do ar e esfriando o ambiente. Parques e florestas urbanas funcionam como ar-condicionado natural da cidade.",
      "title": "Ar-Condicionado Verde"
    },
    {
      "text": "Combustíveis como gasolina e carvão são fotossíntese fossilizada. A energia no tanque do carro veio de plantas que capturaram luz solar há milhões de anos.",
      "title": "Energia Ancestral"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando você vê plantas de aquário borbulhando, está vendo fotossíntese ao vivo. Aquelas bolhas são oxigênio puro sendo liberado na água, mantendo os peixes vivos.",
      "title": "Bolhas no Aquário"
    },
    {
      "text": "Campos de soja e milho são fazendas solares gigantes. Agricultores plantam milhões de \"captadores de luz\" que convertem raios do sol em alimento para o mundo todo.",
      "title": "Fazendas de Luz"
    },
    {
      "text": "O fitoplâncton nos oceanos faz metade da fotossíntese do planeta. Esses seres microscópicos produzem mais oxigênio que todas as florestas tropicais juntas.",
      "title": "Heróis Invisíveis do Mar"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando ambientalistas falam em salvar florestas para combater mudanças climáticas, é fotossíntese em ação. Árvores sugam CO2 do ar e estocam carbono em troncos e raízes.",
      "title": "Escudo Climático Natural"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Cada vez que compras en Amazon o pagas en Mercado Libre, tus datos bancarios viajan encriptados. Por eso puedes ingresar tu tarjeta sin que nadie en el camino pueda leerla.",
      "title": "Compras Online"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tus mensajes de WhatsApp están encriptados de extremo a extremo. Ni la empresa ni tu proveedor de internet pueden leer lo que escribes — solo tú y tu contacto.",
      "title": "Mensajes de WhatsApp"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando ingresas tu contraseña en Netflix o Facebook, la encriptación protege ese momento vulnerable. Nadie husmeando la red WiFi del café puede capturar tu clave.",
      "title": "Inicio de Sesión"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tu celular encripta todas las fotos, contactos y mensajes almacenados. Si alguien roba tu teléfono bloqueado, encuentra solo datos ilegibles sin tu PIN o huella digital.",
      "title": "Datos en Tu Celular"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las videollamadas de Zoom usan encriptación para que tu reunión laboral o llamada familiar permanezca privada. Tus conversaciones no flotan desprotegidas por internet.",
      "title": "Videollamadas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tu correo de Gmail viaja encriptado entre tu computadora y los servidores. Aunque pase por múltiples redes, nadie puede interceptar y leer tus emails personales o laborales.",
      "title": "Email Personal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las apps bancarias encriptan cada consulta de saldo y transferencia. Por eso puedes revisar tus finanzas desde cualquier red sin exponer cuánto dinero tienes.",
      "title": "Banca Móvil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Netflix y Spotify encriptan tu contenido streaming. Aunque suene extraño proteger películas, esto evita que terceros rastreen exactamente qué miras o escuchas.",
      "title": "Streaming de Entretenimiento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los documentos en Google Drive o Dropbox se encriptan al subirse y almacenarse. Tus archivos personales o contratos importantes permanecen privados en la nube.",
      "title": "Almacenamiento en la Nube"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las redes WiFi con contraseña encriptan todo el tráfico entre tu dispositivo y el router. Por eso es más seguro que el WiFi abierto de aeropuertos o plazas.",
      "title": "WiFi Protegido"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "When you're searching for a gift online and every site suddenly shows ads for that item, you're in a positive feedback loop. Your clicks signal interest, triggering more recommendations, which you click again, feeding the cycle until your entire feed reflects one shopping quest.",
      "title": "Your Targeted Ad Spiral"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ever notice how hard it is to break a bad sleep schedule? Stay up late once, you're tired the next day, so you nap. That makes falling asleep at night harder, so you stay up later again. Each late night reinforces the next in a self-perpetuating cycle.",
      "title": "The Sleep Schedule Trap"
    },
    {
      "text": "In online meetings, when someone says \"Can you hear me?\" and no one responds, they repeat louder. Still silence. They shout. Turns out they were muted — a negative feedback loop failed. Without confirmation signals circling back, the system couldn't stabilize.",
      "title": "The Muted Meeting Mystery"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your home's furnace demonstrates negative feedback perfectly. Temperature drops below 68°F, heat kicks on. Once it hits 70°F, heat shuts off. The system constantly opposes its own output to maintain balance, never letting temperature run away in either direction.",
      "title": "Thermostat Dance"
    },
    {
      "text": "Panic buying creates its own reality. News mentions possible shortages, people stock up \"just in case,\" shelves actually empty, more people panic-buy, supply genuinely runs short. The fear of shortage produces the shortage through amplifying feedback.",
      "title": "The Toilet Paper Phenomenon"
    },
    {
      "text": "When a song goes viral on TikTok, early popularity triggers the algorithm to show it more, which creates more videos using it, which signals more popularity, which boosts it further. Each play amplifies the next until it's unavoidable on your feed.",
      "title": "Viral Song Explosion"
    },
    {
